            <!-- Explanatory content -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>
                How this construction concrete quantities &amp; masonry
                calculator works
              </h2>
              <p>
                This tool combines several professional concrete and masonry
                calculators into a single interface. It supports both imperial
                and metric units and converts results to cubic yards and cubic
                meters so you can order from any supplier.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Concrete volume formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Slab / pad (rectangular):</strong></p>
                <p>Volume = Length × Width × Thickness</p>
                <p>
                  In imperial units the calculator converts thickness from
                  inches to feet before multiplying, then converts cubic feet to
                  cubic yards:
                </p>
                <p>
                  $$V_{yd^3} = \frac{L_{ft} \times W_{ft} \times
                  T_{in}/12}{27}$$
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Footing / strip:</strong></p>
                <p>Volume = Total length × Width × Thickness</p>
                <p>
                  Again, width and thickness are converted from inches to feet,
                  then to cubic yards.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Round column / sonotube:</strong></p>
                <p>$$V = \pi \times \left(\frac{D}{2}\right)^2 \times H$$</p>
                <p>
                  Where D is diameter and H is height (converted to consistent
                  units).
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Square / rectangular column or wall:</strong></p>
                <p>Volume = Length × Width × Height</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Bag count and waste allowance</h3>
              <p>
                Once the total volume is known, the calculator estimates the
                number of premix bags based on typical yields:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>40 lb bag ≈ 0.30 ft³</li>
                <li>60 lb bag ≈ 0.45 ft³</li>
                <li>80 lb bag ≈ 0.60 ft³</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The number of bags is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  $$\text{Bags} = \frac{V_{ft^3}}{\text{Yield per bag
                  (ft}^3\text{)}}$$
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The tool also shows a recommended order with 10% extra to cover
                waste, spillage, and uneven subgrade.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Masonry block and mortar estimation</h3>
              <p>For masonry walls, the calculator first computes wall area:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Wall area = Length × Height</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Then it estimates the number of blocks based on the face area of
                a block plus mortar joint. For a standard 8×8×16 in block with
                3/8 in joints, the effective face size is about 16 in × 8 in, or
                1.125 ft × 0.667 ft.
              </p>
              <p>Blocks per square foot is approximately:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Blocks/ft² ≈ 1 / (Block length × Block height)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator then adds 5% extra blocks for cuts and breakage.
              </p>
              <p>
                Mortar volume is estimated using typical consumption rates per
                square meter of wall, adjusted for block size. This is converted
                to cubic yards and approximate bags of mortar mix.
              </p>

              <h3>Practical tips for accurate estimates</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Measure in multiple places:</strong> For slabs and
                  footings, measure thickness at several points and use the
                  greatest value.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Account for sub-base:</strong> Concrete volume does
                  not include gravel or compacted base; add those separately.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round up orders:</strong> Ready-mix suppliers usually
                  deliver in 0.5 or 1.0 yd³ increments. Always round up to the
                  next increment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check local codes:</strong> Minimum footing and wall
                  thicknesses are often specified by building codes or
                  engineers.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How much extra concrete should I order?</h3>
              <p>
                Most contractors add 5–10% to the calculated volume. For small
                DIY projects, 10% is common because small errors in measurement
                or subgrade compaction can be significant.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for irregular shapes?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, break the shape into rectangles or simple sections,
                calculate each section separately using the appropriate tab,
                then add the volumes together.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my supplier quotes in cubic meters?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator always shows both cubic yards and cubic meters.
                Use the m³ value when talking to metric suppliers.
              </p>

              <h3>How accurate are the masonry mortar estimates?</h3>
              <p>
                Mortar consumption depends on workmanship, joint thickness, and
                waste. The calculator uses typical industry averages, which are
                suitable for planning and ordering, but your actual usage may
                vary by ±10–20%.
              </p>
            </section>
